On “simulation theory”:

In this view, the sense of living in a “simulation” does not arise from an external machine or higher‑order civilization running a program. Instead, it emerges from the internal dynamics of distinction, marking, and reentry — the basic operations through which a system brings forth both a self (“I”) and a world (“not‑I”). The simulation is not something imposed from outside; it is the ongoing recursive process by which the system organizes its own experience.

The “I” is not a metaphysical subject but the stabilized pattern of constraints generated by past distinctions. The “world” is simply whatever lies outside that constraint structure. Because each new distinction must remain compatible with the accumulated history, the system develops internal lawfulness and coherence. This coupling between the self‑producing process and the domain it distinguishes is what gives rise to the feeling of inhabiting a rule‑governed, constructed reality.

No external semantics are required. Meaning emerges from the correlations produced by recursive constraint propagation. The system “simulates” a world only in the sense that it continually generates a coherent pattern of distinctions that maintain its own identity. The simulation is therefore contextual: it exists only in the relationship between the self‑maintaining process and the environment it enacts as “not‑I.”

This interpretation avoids the metaphysical problems of traditional “simulation theory” — no infinite regress, no hidden simulator, no dualism between “real” and “simulated.” Instead, the simulation is intrinsic to the dynamics of self‑organization. The experience of being in a simulation is simply the phenomenology of a system that maintains itself through recursive distinctions, generating both a self and a world in the process.

----------

Nagel’s formulation of consciousness treats it as requiring an additional fact beyond physical or functional organization: that there exists “something it is like” for the system itself. This introduces a first-person ontological commitment that is, in principle, inaccessible from third-person description.

The 2-bit reentrant model of primitive consciousness avoids this requirement by declining to treat “what-it-is-like-ness” as a separate property at all. Instead, it identifies appearance with the system’s operational capacity to register and stabilize distinctions under recursive constraint. In this view, no further experiential ingredient is posited beyond the dynamics of state, memory, and rule-conditioned marking. What would ordinarily be called phenomenology is reinterpreted as the internal organization of distinction-handling processes rather than as an intrinsic qualitative residue.

Consequently, the model circumvents Nagel’s criterion not by denying experience, but by dissolving the need for an irreducible first-person category. “Something it is like to be” is replaced by a fully structural description: the degree to which a system preserves and applies constraints when marking stochastically arising distinctions. Consciousness, on this account, becomes a property of recursive informational organization rather than of private subjective presence.

